article.headline: Wis.-Milwaukee 76, Ill.-Chicago 65
article.story: MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Avery Smith scored 19 points and Paige Paulsen 18 and Wisconsin-Milwaukee nailed a school record 12 3-pointers in the first half to defeat Illinois-Chicago 76-65 in a Horizon League game Wednesday night. The Panthers made 12-of-19 3-pointers in the opening period to lead 48-25. Milwaukee's previous record for 3-pointers in a half was 11, made Dec. 30, 2001, against Colorado and tied against Prairie View A&M Nov. 20, 2004. The Panthers' record for 3-pointers in a game is 18, made Jan. 11, 2001, in a 114-106 four-overtime loss to the Flames. The Panthers (6-14, 3-4) also got 15 points from Allan Hanson and 14 from Ricky Franklin. The Flames (9-10, 4-2) were knocked out of a first-place conference tie with Wright State, which was idle. Othyus Jeffers scored 23 points for Chicago. Chicago coach Jimmy Collins has been sidelined since Jan. 4 while he recovers from an abdominal aortic aneurysm. Associate head coach Mark Coomes ran the team. The Panthers lost their long-range touch in the second half, missing all seven 3-pointers they tried. However, Milwaukee's 23-point halftime lead was too much for Chicago, which kept nibbling away at the Panther advantage but could pull no closer than 8 points at 72-64 on a 3-pointer by T.J. Gray with 1:14 left to play. Jeffers tied the game at 21-21 with 8:30 left in the first half before the Panthers made five straight 3-pointers for a 36-21 lead. Franklin had three of them.
